 <h1 class="text-center">PYTHAGORAS</h1>
 <h1 class="text-center">––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––</font></h1>
 <h3 class="text-center"><em>"A thought is an idea in transit."</em></h3>
</header>

 <div>
  <center>
   <a href="http://www.hermes-press.com/Pythagoras-Knapp.gif" target="_blank"> <img id="pic1" class="black-border img-responsive" alt="Painting of Pythagoras standing with his work." src="http://www.hermes-press.com/Pythagoras-Knapp.gif" width="800"></a>
  </center>
  <h3><font size="5" color="#0070d2">Pythagoras (Πυθαγόρας), a Greek philosopher and mathematician</h3> </font>
 </div>

 <br><br>
 <div>

  <span style="font-size: 13.5pt; color:black; text-align:justify; font-family: sans-serif">
   <h3>Overview of Pythagoras:</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Born in Samos, an island off the Ionian coast c. 570 BC.</li>
  <li>During the persian invasion, Pythagoras left and settled in croton, Itlay, where he opened a school for religious and scientific studies.</li>
  <li>2 issues arise in studying Pythagoras' works:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>All the discorveries made by the commnuity were attributed to Pythagoras, even after he had died for many years. Therefore, we are unsure of Pythogoras' own ideas.</li>
      <li>Since the community was a exclusive society, no written document was made. We only have secondhand accounts, some of which are from those who were never members of the school.</li>
    </ol></ul>
  <h3>Pythagorean school of thought:</h3>
  <ul>
  <li>Members of the Pythagorean school were under 5-year inititation period, where the new member must observe silence.</li>
  <li>Pythagoreans believed in reincarnations, thus they asbstain from eating meat.</li>
  <li>3 fundemental principles of Pythagrianism: purification, contemplation, and order.</li>
  <li>Pythagoras held that the 1st principle of nature is <em>numbers</em>, leading us the quantative science.</li>
  <li>Best known for coming up with the<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem" target="_blank"> Pythagorean theorem</a>. > <span style="color: #ff4080"> Scoll down to explore various proofs</span></li>
  <li>Pythagoras lso discovered the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commensurability_(mathematics)" target="_blank"> principle of incommensurability </a>(irrational numbers).</li>
  <li>For Pythagoreans: even numbers represent the unlimited, odd numbers the limited. Here's a visual explaination:</li>
  <p>Consider a set of units arranged in form of square below: </p>

  <p><img width="650px" src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/d/1ZeMeD6rWVoLIJ4jJ7l_1FxJ7XSNgvadQwL82DIDjogE/pub?w=1119&h=355" />
   <p id="explain"><span style="font:12pt">
        If you bisect the odd-numbered square (left), you get 3 units on each side of the right angeled triangle, with nothing left over. If you bisect the even-numbered square, you get additional units over on one side.
     </p></span> &nbsp;
    <li>Pythoreans associated the finite with order and rationality, the infinite with disorder and irrationality.</li>
    <li>To Pythagoras, "1" is not a number becuase number implies plurality –"2" is the beginning of pluralilty.</li>
    </span>
 </div>

